The output of mpiram is stored as a direct access, binary file, "psif.dat".  
To read this file, one must know the record length that was used when it 
was written.  This record length likely depends on the compiler.  For this 
reason, when the code writes the binary data file, it also writes out, or 
saves, the record length value to "recl.dat".

For the gfortran compiler, the record length can be computed as:

  fc=75; Q=2; T=15; 
% fc is center frequency, Q is Q, T is the expected width in seconds of the
% acoustic arrival pattern.  All specified in the input file.
  nzo=1;
% nzo is length of zg1(1), or 1.
  fs=4*fc;
% sample frequency is 4*center frequency
  bw=fc/Q;
% bandwidth
  df=fs/(fs*T);
% frequency increment
  nf=floor((bw-df)/df) + 1;
% number of frequencies of one sign
  nf=2*nf+1;
% total number of frequencies
  recl=(4*nzo) + 2*((4*nf));  
% compute the record length - (4 bytes per number?)

